  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several important ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Palermo Convention\n- These establish global standards and frameworks for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute cross-border money laundering\n- Sharing of financial intelligence and legal evidence\n- Extradition agreements for money laundering suspects\n\n3. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Standardizing anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Implementing consistent reporting requirements\n- Developing common definitions and legal approaches\n\n4. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must follow international standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n\n5. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- International sanctions\n- Asset freezing and seizure\n- Coordinated investigations across jurisdictions\n\n6. Information Sharing Platforms\n- Interpol\n- Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units\n- Facilitating international cooperation and intelligence exchange\n\nThese intersections create a comprehensive global approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering activities.",
